04596nam a22005895i 9780822381815DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20131993ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223818157 a10.1515/97808223818152doi  a(DE-B1597)552831  a(OCoLC)1202623266  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aPOL0280002bisacsh  aAK 290002rvk04aThe Argumentative Turn in Policy Analysis and Planning /cFrank Fischer, John Forester. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2013] 4cÂ©1993  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tEditors' Introduction -- tPolicy Discourse and the Politics of Washington Think Tanks -- tDiscourse Coalitions and the Institutionalization of Practice: The Case of Acid Rain in Great Britain -- tPolitical Judgment and the Policy Cycle: The Case of Ethnicity Policy Arguments in the Netherlands -- tCounsel and Consensus: Norms of Argument in Health Policy -- tSurvey Research as Rhetorical Trope: Electric Power Planning Arguments in Chicago -- tReframing Policy Discourse -- tReading Policy Narratives: Beginnings, Middles, and Ends -- tLearning from Practice Stories: The Priority of Practical Judgment -- tPolicy Analysis and Planning: From Science to Argument -- tPlanning Through Debate: The Communicative Turn in Planning Theory -- tPolicy Reforms as Arguments -- tGuidelines for Policy Discourse: Consensual versus Adversarial -- tContributors -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPublic policy is made of language. Whether in written or oral form, argument is central to all parts of the policy process. As simple as this insight appears, its implications for policy analysis and planning are profound. Drawing from recent work on language and argumentation and referring to such theorists as Wittgenstein, Habermas, Toulmin, and Foucault, these essays explore the interplay of language, action, and power in both the practice and the theory of policy-making.The contributors, scholars of international renown who range across the theoretical spectrum, emphasize the political nature of the policy planner's work and stress the role of persuasive arguments in practical decision making. Recognizing the rhetorical, communicative character of policy and planning deliberations, they show that policy arguments are necessarily selective, both shaping and being shaped by relations of power. These essays reveal the practices of policy analysts and planners in powerful new ways--as matters of practical argumentation in complex, highly political environments. They also make an important contribution to contemporary debates over postempiricism in the social and policy sciences.Contributors. John S. Dryzek, William N. Dunn, Frank Fischer, John Forester, Maarten Hajer, Patsy Healey, Robert Hoppe, Bruce Jennings, Thomas J. Kaplan, Duncan MacRae, Jr., Martin Rein, Donald Schon, J. A. Throgmorton  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aDebates and debating. 0aPersuasion (Rhetoric). 0aPolicy sciences. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / General.2bisacsh1 aFischer, Frank, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aForester, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHajer, Maarten A.1 aHoppe, Robert1 aJennings, Bruce08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822381815zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822381815423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822381815.jpg  a978-3-11-071360-2  DUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHA